The paper deals with problems related to computational geometry, discrete mathematics, and optimization. Specifically, it discusses the problem of partitioning a set of points in $\mathbb{R}^d$ into convex bodies, which is a fundamental problem in computational geometry (cs.CG). It also presents an approximation algorithm for computing the maximum volume of an empty convex body, which involves optimization and numerical analysis (cs.NA). The paper also mentions a connection to a famous problem of Danzer and Rogers, which is related to discrete geometry (cs.DM) and geometric topology (cs.GT). Finally, the paper discusses the complexity of the problem and gives lower and upper bounds, which are related to computational complexity (cs.DS).
